================================================================================
TROUBLESHOOTING: GKE Backends UNHEALTHY + Image Not Updating After Redeploy
================================================================================
Date: 2026-03-12
Services: poll-service, vote-service, poker-planning-service
Cluster: REDACTED_GKE_CLUSTER (REDACTED_GKE_ZONE)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PROBLEM SUMMARY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

After rebuilding and pushing Docker images, two issues were found:

1. kubectl rollout restart was NOT deploying the new image — pods kept running
   the old code.

2. GCP Load Balancer backends showed UNHEALTHY for all three services in
   kubectl describe ingress, making the app unreachable via REDACTED_DOMAIN.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ROOT CAUSE 1 — imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Both poll-deployment.yaml and vote-deployment.yaml had:
  imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent

This tells Kubernetes: "only pull the image if it is not already on the node."
Since the image tag (:latest) never changes, GKE assumes the cached image on the
node is still valid and skips the pull — even after a new image was pushed to
Artifact Registry.

Fix: change to imagePullPolicy: Always in both deployment files.
This forces GKE to contact Artifact Registry on every pod start and pull the
latest image.

Affected files:
  live-poll-app/poll-deployment.yaml
  live-poll-app/vote-deployment.yaml

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ROOT CAUSE 2 — Docker build layer cache serving stale code
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Even after switching to imagePullPolicy: Always, the built image still contained
old code. This is because Docker caches each build step (layer). The COPY . .
step was cached from a previous build and Docker did not detect the file change.

Fix: use --no-cache flag when building to force Docker to re-execute every step.

  docker build --no-cache -t <image> ./live-poll-app

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ROOT CAUSE 3 — BackendConfig using wrong port for health checks
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

GKE uses NEGs (Network Endpoint Groups) when a Service has the annotation:
  cloud.google.com/neg: '{"ingress": true}'

With NEGs, GCP's load balancer health checks probe pods DIRECTLY at their
container IP and port — bypassing the Kubernetes Service entirely.

The original BackendConfig (poker-backend-config) was configured with:
  port: 80
  requestPath: /

But poll-service and vote-service containers listen on port 3001, not 80.
So the GCP health check was hitting the wrong port and getting no response,
marking backends as UNHEALTHY.

Additionally, a single BackendConfig was shared across all three services via
the ingress annotation:
  cloud.google.com/backend-config: '{"default": "poker-backend-config"}'

The frontend (poker-planning) runs on port 80, but the API services run on 3001,
so one config cannot work for both.

Fix: create two separate BackendConfigs and attach them per-service (not on
the ingress), then remove the global annotation from the ingress.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SOLUTION — What was changed
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

backend-config.yaml (replaced single config with two):

  apiVersion: cloud.google.com/v1
  kind: BackendConfig
  metadata:
    name: api-backend-config       # for poll-service and vote-service
  spec:
    healthCheck:
      port: 3001
      requestPath: /
      type: HTTP
      checkIntervalSec: 15
  ---
  apiVersion: cloud.google.com/v1
  kind: BackendConfig
  metadata:
    name: frontend-backend-config  # for poker-planning-service
  spec:
    healthCheck:
      port: 80
      requestPath: /
      type: HTTP
      checkIntervalSec: 15

poll-service.yaml and vote-service.yaml — added annotation:
  cloud.google.com/backend-config: '{"default": "api-backend-config"}'

poker-planning-deployment.yaml (Service section) — added annotation:
  cloud.google.com/backend-config: '{"default": "frontend-backend-config"}'

poll-ingress.yaml — removed the global annotation:
  cloud.google.com/backend-config: '{"default": "poker-backend-config"}'  ← deleted

poll-deployment.yaml and vote-deployment.yaml:
  imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent  →  imagePullPolicy: Always

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FULL REDEPLOY PROCEDURE (use this for all future deployments)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 1 — Authenticate Docker with GCP (first time or after token expiry)
  gcloud auth configure-docker REDACTED_REGISTRY_HOST

Step 2 — Get GKE credentials (first time or on new machine)
  gcloud container clusters get-credentials REDACTED_GKE_CLUSTER \
    --zone REDACTED_GKE_ZONE --project REDACTED_GCP_PROJECT_ID

Step 3 — Build images (always use --no-cache to avoid stale layers)
  docker build --no-cache -t REDACTED_REGISTRY_HOST/REDACTED_GCP_PROJECT_ID/poker-repo/poll-service:latest ./live-poll-app
  docker build --no-cache -t REDACTED_REGISTRY_HOST/REDACTED_GCP_PROJECT_ID/poker-repo/vote-service:latest ./live-poll-app/vote-service

Step 4 — Push images to Artifact Registry
  docker push REDACTED_REGISTRY_HOST/REDACTED_GCP_PROJECT_ID/poker-repo/poll-service:latest
  docker push REDACTED_REGISTRY_HOST/REDACTED_GCP_PROJECT_ID/poker-repo/vote-service:latest

Step 5 — Trigger rolling restart in GKE
  kubectl rollout restart deployment/poll-service-deployment deployment/vote-service-deployment

Step 6 — Wait for rollout
  kubectl rollout status deployment/poll-service-deployment
  kubectl rollout status deployment/vote-service-deployment

Step 7 — Verify pods are running
  kubectl get pods

Step 8 — Test health endpoint directly inside a pod
  kubectl exec $(kubectl get pod -l app=poll-service -o jsonpath='{.items[0].metadata.name}') \
    -- sh -c "wget -qO- http://localhost:3001/"
  kubectl exec $(kubectl get pod -l app=vote-service -o jsonpath='{.items[0].metadata.name}') \
    -- sh -c "wget -qO- http://localhost:3001/"

Step 9 — Check GCP load balancer backend health (takes 5-10 min to update)
  kubectl describe ingress
  # Look for "HEALTHY" in ingress.kubernetes.io/backends

