USEFUL DIAGNOSTIC COMMANDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Check what image is actually running in a pod:
  kubectl exec <pod-name> -- sh -c "wc -l /app/server.js"

Check routes in a running pod:
  kubectl exec <pod-name> -- sh -c "grep 'app.get\|app.listen' /app/server.js"

Check service annotations (BackendConfig, NEG):
  kubectl get svc poll-service vote-service poker-planning-service \
    -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.name}: {.metadata.annotations}{"\n"}{end}'

List all BackendConfigs:
  kubectl get backendconfig

View recent events (errors, image pulls, restarts):
  kubectl get events --sort-by='.lastTimestamp'

Check GCP backend health status:
  kubectl describe ingress | grep -A3 "backends:"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
KEY CONCEPTS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

NEG (Network Endpoint Group):
  When a Service has cloud.google.com/neg: '{"ingress": true}', GCP routes
  traffic directly to pod IPs instead of through the ClusterIP Service.
  Health checks also probe pods directly, so the port in BackendConfig must
  match the container port (containerPort), not the Service port.

BackendConfig:
  A GKE CRD that controls GCP load balancer settings (health checks, timeouts,
  CDN, etc.) for a specific Service. Attach it to the Service annotation
  cloud.google.com/backend-config, not to the Ingress, when you need different
  configs per service.

imagePullPolicy: Always vs IfNotPresent:
  Always      → Kubernetes pulls from registry on every pod start. Required
                when using mutable tags like :latest.
  IfNotPresent → Kubernetes skips the pull if the image is already on the node.
                Safe only with immutable tags (e.g. v1.2.3).

Docker build cache:
  Docker caches each layer. If source files change but Docker does not detect
  the difference (e.g. file timestamps), it reuses the cached COPY layer and
  the new code is not included. Use --no-cache to bypass this.

GCP health check propagation delay:
  After changing BackendConfig, GCP takes 5-10 minutes to update the load
  balancer. During this time, pods can be healthy while GCP still shows
  UNHEALTHY. This is normal — wait and re-check.

